Design Tensor v1.0 — The Three Signal Sisters

Core Claim

All effective output (content, product, communication) is governed by three interacting axes:

Taste (T) · Judgment (J) · Position (P)

⸻

Formal Definition

Let an output artifact be A

Then its effective signal strength:

S(A) = T × J × P

Where:
	•	T (Taste) ∈ [0,1] — aesthetic and signal discrimination
	•	J (Judgment) ∈ [0,1] — functional correctness and decision quality
	•	P (Position) ∈ [0,1] — contextual alignment (audience, timing, placement)

⸻

Interpretation
	•	Multiplicative system → any weak axis collapses total signal
	•	Non-linear → improvements in the weakest axis yield the largest gains
	•	Domain-agnostic → applies to writing, apps, UX, business, strategy

⸻

Axis Definitions (Operational)

1. Taste — Signal Filtering Layer

“Is this clean, coherent, and resonant?”

Function:
	•	Separates signal from noise before execution

Indicators:
	•	Simplicity over clutter
	•	Coherence of style
	•	Emotional/intuitive resonance

Failure Modes:
	•	Noise inflation (too much, too messy)
	•	Aesthetic incoherence
	•	Derivative without refinement

⸻

2. Judgment — Decision & Constraint Layer

“Does this actually work?”

Function:
	•	Selects viable paths under real constraints

Indicators:
	•	Correct prioritization
	•	Tradeoff awareness
	•	Reality alignment (what survives contact)

Failure Modes:
	•	Technically wrong / impractical
	•	Over-engineered or under-scoped
	•	Ignores constraints (time, user, system)

⸻

3. Position — Context & Delivery Layer

“Does this land where it matters?”

Function:
	•	Aligns output with environment

Indicators:
	•	Right audience
	•	Right timing
	•	Right medium/channel

Failure Modes:
	•	Invisible (wrong channel)
	•	Misaligned (wrong audience)
	•	Poor timing (too early / too late)

⸻

Interaction Rules

Rule 1 — Multiplicative Collapse

If any axis ≈ 0 → S(A) ≈ 0

⸻

Rule 2 — Bottleneck Priority

Optimize the lowest axis first

⸻

Rule 3 — Overcompensation Illusion

High strength in one axis cannot compensate for failure in another
	•	High Taste + Low Judgment → “beautiful failure”
	•	High Judgment + Low Taste → “effective but ignored”
	•	High T+J + Low Position → “great but unseen”

⸻

Rule 4 — Translation Layer Independence

Formatting, tooling, and medium conversion do not increase S(A)
They only preserve or degrade it.

(Handled by translation layer, not the tensor)

⸻

Evaluation Function (Practical Use)

Score each axis (0–10):

T = ?
J = ?
P = ?

S = (T/10) × (J/10) × (P/10)


⸻

Optimization Loop
	1.	Identify weakest axis
	2.	Apply targeted correction
	3.	Re-evaluate
	4.	Iterate until balanced

⸻

Diagnostic Table

Symptom	Likely Deficit
Looks good but fails in use	Judgment
Works but nobody cares	Taste or Position
Strong idea, no traction	Position
Cluttered / confusing	Taste
Overcomplicated / impractical	Judgment
Posted but ignored	Position


⸻

System Boundary

The Design Tensor governs:
	•	Creation quality
	•	Communication clarity
	•	Product viability

It does not govern:
	•	Distribution scale (separate system)
	•	Raw compute / tooling
	•	External randomness (luck, noise)

⸻

Integration with Translation Layer

Intent → (Design Tensor applied) → Structured Output → Translation Layer → Multi-format Render

	•	Tensor = what should exist
	•	Translation layer = how it manifests across mediums

⸻

Compact Doctrine

“Make it right (Taste), make it work (Judgment), make it land (Position).”

